title: Chelan Cafe
text:
Well my friends, here's a great place to have a bite; breakfast, lunch, and dinner.
We stopped in for breakfast, and the ladies were inviting and held great breakfast conversations. Didn't really expect much but I found a nice little corner to have a quality breakfast and a chance to be silly in the morning.
The traffic wasn't bad but this place is located near the industrial area of the Port of Seattle so there's some big trucks in the morning.
I still really enjoy the restaurant, nice job Chelan Cafe.
Oh and by the way this place has no ties to Lake Chelan WA. I wish I love Lake Chelan.

title: Queen Sheba Ethiopian Restaurant
text:
The food was not even close to what I expected it to be. This restaurant doesn't care about the quality of Ethiopian food they give because they are not facing any competition in the area it's located.
Am never going back. I gave it two star because the waitress was sweet nice lady.

Please go to other Ethiopian restaurants such as Enaat, Saba, chef cafe,.. etc

title: Volunteer Park Cafe & Pantry
text: Cute! Menu is a little small compared to the old owners but I‚Äôm so happy to see this space vibrant again. Feels more cafe than full restaurant but I still love it. Amazing baked goods in the case and wonderful coffee. Absolutely packed on a Friday morning, lots of space outside as the weather warms up. Love the larder vibes but wish there was maybe more seating. So cute though.

title: Volunteer Park Cafe & Pantry
text:
Very nice cafe/restaurant. Good coffee, but service is poor.

More than 40 minutes for a grilled cheese sandwich (still waiting as I write this). The place isn't even full. I would probably try it again next time but it won't be my top priority.

Update:
see photo of very sad grilled cheese w/c took 45+ minutes to prepare.

title: Volunteer Park Cafe & Pantry
text:
While the staff at this establishment continue to provide excellent service and food quality, I must mention the deplorable behavior of owner Ericka Burke. Never before have I witnessed such callous, selfish, and reckless actions. When a neighborhood plumbing renovation brought raw sewage water into the restaurant's pipes, Miss Burke demanded to keep the restaurant open even after her staff closed for the day in order to protect customers from serious illness. The implications of her irresponsible wishes in this situation are staggering. This woman should not be allowed to serve food to the public, since she is clearly more concerned with making money than with providing her customers safe food.

Perhaps more repugnant even than allowing raw sewage into her food, is the manner in which Miss Burke treats her staff. I have frequently seen her yell at her serving and cook staff in front of customers, even using profanities with children in the restaurant. In spite of her ridiculously unprofessional behavior, Volunteer Park Cafe's competant staff remains loyal to the local customers who have come to love VPC's family-friendly atmosphere, which is strongly bolstered by baker and co-owner Heather Earnhardt. It is clear to all who visit this restaurant that it is only Heather's efforts and constant presence that keep VPC running smoothly.

Ericka Burke should be ashamed of herself. She obviously wants only to make a name for herself by stepping on the backs of the people below her. Bouncing checks to her food purveyors, failing to pay her employees on time if at all, and providing false information to unemployment services are among some of her frequent improprieties.

I can only trust that some day, her wickedness will come back ten-fold, as it so often does with people as self-serving, greedy, and malicious as this woman.

title: Pagliacci Pizza
text: Ordered margarita pizza... simple right? NOOOOO THEY BURNT IT AND I WAS THE ONLY CUSTOMER IN THE ENTIRE RESTAURANT!!! I WALK OUT FROM THE  RESTAURANT VERY HUNGRY AND WENT TO BELLE EPICUREAN CAFEüò≠üò†

title: Cafe Flora
text:
The food at Cafe Flora tastes about okay and that's just my personal preference. The one thing I liked is their high tea offering last year as it had a vegan option. I'd have given them 4 stars but I don't find their customer experience great hence the 2 stars.

The staff at the restaurant and the team managing their Instagram account don't seem like the kindest people out there hence I'd consider going to another restaurant instead of coming here.

title: Cafe Flora
text: Cafe Flora is a must try! I tried to kale caesar salad, southern breakfast platter with tofu scramble, and of course the massive cinnamon. Kale salad was ok, but the rest was phenomenal. Everything tasted fresh and incredibly flavorful. The restaurant is beautiful and comfortable. Staff is efficient and friendly. It was very busy but I was eating alone and was seated quickly. Just about everything in the menu can be made vegan. Will be back for more tofu scramble and cinnamon roll!

title: Cafe Flora
text: I had an amazing dining experience at Cafe Flora. The vegetarian menu offered an impressive variety of flavorful dishes, and the presentation was really good. The cozy ambiance and friendly staff made the meal even more enjoyable. I highly recommend this restaurant to anyone looking for exceptional vegetarian cuisine.

title: Cafe Flora
text:
Cafe flora has been my go to restaurant since for their creative and tasty vegan options! Every time i have a family or friend, this is my go to place to bring them.

My complaint is that, we were a given a table right next to the bathroom when i could see enough other empty tables. I hope the service gets better.

title: Cafe Flora
text:
Amazing place with the best breakfast in Seattle. Yes it's vegetarian, but you don't miss out on anything. They know how to cook the perfect scrambles, their biscuits and gravy is better than any I've had before, and I love their cheesy grits.

The atrium is such a pleasant experience with the natural light and plants they have, but the whole restaurant is just a great atmosphere.

We've never had bad service here ever, everyone is always fun, positive, and attentive.

We love Cafe Flora.

title: Cafe Flora
text: Charming vegan restaurant with natural decor accented by live plants and open concept. Indoor or outdoor seating takes advantage of the temperate weather of Seattle  and can be enjoyed any time of year. Among the best brunch spots in Seattle, be sure to arrive early on weekends or roll the dice for a longer wait time since it is hoppin' ! Appreciated the all gender restrooms and super kind and energetic staff. I definitely recommend Cafe Flora!!!

title: Cafe Flora
text: The valentine's day dinner was a decadent and flavorful masterpiece. all the food was vegan for this event and each plate was totally worth the price. The wine pairing was good as well but a good cocktail from the menu is slightly cheaper and pairs well with all the courses. my husband had the perfect date which was noor date infused bourbon. well worth the money and a wonderful experience. I even received seconds on the third course because I loved it so much! Thank you Cafe Flora for being the best restaurant meal I've ever had!

title: Cafe Flora
text:
I visited Cafe Flora based on a friend‚Äôs recommendation, and it surpassed expectations. I love trying quirky/creative vegetarian and vegan restaurants, and this one definitely fit the bill!

We called ahead (30 min) since we were a larger party of 8, and they had the table ready when we got there, even though they don‚Äôt take reservations. The table location wasn‚Äôt ideal since it was by the door to their outdoor seating area and there was a frequent cold breeze, but thoughtful nonetheless. Our waiter was super friendly, which made our experience even more memorable.

We ordered nearly the entire menu and shared everything family style. My favorites were the brussel sprouts, coconut tofu lettuce wraps, eggplant & bell pepper campanelle, and turkish cauliflower polenta. The flavor profile for each of these was pretty complex and balanced.

A few of us got drinks - the mulled wine, wakey wakey, and rosemary lemon drop - which were all pretty delicious and strong. We ended the night with dessert, which were yummy but not neccesarily something to write home about.

Overall, it was a memorable experience and I‚Äôd definitely return if I‚Äôm in the area again! Easily on my top 10 restaurant list.

title: Cafe Flora
text:
Cafe Flora is an institution in Seattle.  One of the first major vegetrian restaurants in the city.  But it has outgrown its pioneering reputation as it has expanded its footprint with a new restaurant and bakery in SeaTac.

Our party of five waited 20 minutes for a table.  Then we waited another 30 minutes before anyone took our order, then once we gave the order we waited another 20 minutes for our food.  Meanwhile our teenage daughter was desperately hungry. When my wife went to the wait staff inquiring when our food would be staff, a waitress said she would "check."

Once the food arrived it was ordinary.  Well and beautifully plated.  But it was generally bland and boring.

I don't blame the wait staff.  Clearly management of the restaurant has left it understaffed.  Our waitress was taking care of 15 tables in our room and disappeared for long periods. Perhaps serving even more tables elsewhere.  A totally unpleasant experience.  Oh and did I say it was my wife's birthday??  What a downer.

title: Cafe Flora
text: Going to Cafe Flora used to be my favorite part of being in Seattle. I was glad that they had kept their mouthwatering coconut cake as they continued to innovate, but over the years it went from being a soft cake with tons of coconut in it and subtle undertones of intricate flavors, to being a super dry cake that's overly sweet and just tastes like frosting. It seems that they've changed recipes, or simply stopped putting in the work that they used to. The restaurant is too expensive for what it is now. Their burger also used to be better, I still love the fries though. They don't have enough vegan options considering what is now doable with vegan food. 20 years ago they were surely the best vegetarian restaurant in Seattle, but they need to catch up now. It was a dollar to add vegan mozzarella to the burger, and it tasted like Daiya. Dairy cheese was cheaper to add, so they tax vegans here. Even if it wasn't Daiya, it sure did taste the same. I was expecting something unique from somewhere that brands themselves as a tad bit "finer" of dining ($$$). Plating is nice. Interior and staff are welcoming

title: Cafe Flora
text:
I found Cafe Flora on HappyCow, which is an app that helps vegans and vegetarians find restaurant options in their area. I'm glad to say that this place definitely didn't disappoint.

As a vegan it can be super difficult to find good restaurant options so every time I find one I feel like I've struck gold. Even though this place isn't entirely vegan, there are enough options that it'll make most vegans very happy. I ordered the Saffron and Lobster Mushroom Risotto and the Madison cocktail.

The Risotto consisted of arborio rice, saffron, and lobster mushrooms among other ingredients. It didn't taste overly indulgent or heavily sweet or savory, rather it just had a very complimentary combination of flavors and a great texture which didn't warrant extra sugar or salt. I love it when menu items don't taste overly greasy or rich and they have a cleaner vibe about them. The Risotto was accompanied with a minimalist Arugula salad with a great lemon vinaigrette. So simple, yet clean. Good dishes don't need a million ingredients, just a handful of quality ones.

The Madison cocktail seemed like a modified Manhattan, using an earl grey infused vermouth rather than a traditional Italian vermouth in a Manhattan. Honestly, I'm not super educated with my liquors so I cannot speak too much to the complexity of the cocktail, but I can tell you that I really enjoyed it.

I'll definitely be coming back.

title: Cafe Flora
text: Cafe Flora is my favorite restaurant in Seattle. Incredible vegetarian cuisine.

title: Cafe Flora
text: Went back to Cafe Flora for some delicious Brussels Sprouts. They do a great job with social distancing in the restaurant. However, after sitting down for an hour, I was asked to leave because there were other people waiting for a table. After buying a full meal, coffee AND tipping 20% to the servers, I was asked to leave a restaurant because I was lingering. Unacceptable. Most people are not dining out often during Covid. So to be asked to leave a restaurant during your one weekly outing is not a great feeling. I may return for the Brussels Sprouts, but I will get these to go, so I don't have to deal with the terrible customer service.

title: Cafe Flora
text: Cafe Flora is a lovely restaurant with a garden feel. The menu has diversity and hits many popular favorites. We tried the oyster mushroom and leek pizza on the gluten free crust and it was tasty. The use of crushed almonds was particularly interesting. We also had the burger and sweet potato fries which met expectations. We finished it off with golden milk tea.

title: Cafe Flora
text: Sunday, August 18, 2019, I took my 2 out of town vegetarian guests to Cafe Flora, which we thought was the best.  First the hostess would not let us sit at the table where there would be no sun in our eyes.  Later the waitress let us move to that table.  One of my guests has food allergies. She ordered a  pizza and made it clear she could not eat onions or she would get ill.  She was half way into the pizza and noticed the onions (hard to notice, so cooked down).  The waitress was very apologetic, said it was a kitchen error, and offered to give a discount on the bill.  The discount was $2!  My guest talked to the manager (who was also the uncooperative hostess) and told her how unsatisfactory a $2 discount was, since she was going to be ill from the pizza. The manager finally took the pizza off the bill.  This would have been done automatically at any other restaurant.  We're not going back there.

title: Palermo Pizza & Pasta Capitol Hill
text: Great pizza and even better service!!! Nothing but great small cafe ambiance, diverse wine selection and quick service. We got a chance to meet one of the owners and she was by far one of the most amazing and glowing personalities we have ever encountered. It is definitely a nice change of pace from your normal busy Seattle restaurant.

title: The Harvest Vine
text: Everything we tried at The Harvest Vine tasted wonderful and was plated beautifully. This was the perfect restaurant for a birthday dinner with my parents :) we ordered a total of 8 dishes, including appetizers, mains, and dessert, to share among the 3 of us, and it was just the right amount. My favorite main dish was the Octopus, which was so soft and not rubbery at all! My favorite vegetable dish was the Spinach. The pine nuts and raisins pair so well with the natural bitterness of the spinach. We ordered 2 desserts, both of which were delicious, but if I had to pick just one to recommend, it‚Äôd be the Flan de Cafe. Everything we ordered (besides the bread) was gluten free, including the chocolate torte (flourless!). Great atmosphere and spectacular service! Looking forward to going back!

title: Otium Grill & Greens
text: A few months ago, I went to this restaurant for breakfast. I was extremely confused because I had to order in the cafe Ladro, select a seat, and then wait for the food to be brought to our table. When I read about their breakfast on their website, I had a very different impression, which is why I found it so confused. I thought the experience would be more personalized, similar to the atmosphere of a restaurant, but it was really confused. The food was good, there was no service for breakfast but people in the cafe Ladro was very nice!

title: Cafe Lago
text: I have been coming to Cafe Lago since I was a student so many years ago. I moved on but I was smitten with the delicate raviolis then and they are still just as good 3 decades later. A ‚Äúmust visit‚Äù recommendation for any trip to Seattle. And sorry but after eating ravioli here, you will not want to get ravioli at any other restaurant. The grilled eggplant also highly recommended.

title: Cafe Lago
text:
Jeans formal ambience.
Upscale Italian restaurant with very good food. The (non Bolognese) lasagna is particularly good. The Bolognese version might be good too, but folks have been going to Cafe Lago for years for the non Bolognese version.
The Caesar salad and bleu cheese salad are both very good. I also recommend the bruschetta appetizer.
Prices are a bit high, but maybe I just need to recalibrate to pay COVID higher prices for everything.

title: Cafe Lago
text: Cafe Lago is a Seattle institution. We have been going there for almost 15 years. They are known for their feather light lasagna. I had their pea-mint-ricotta ravioli in a lemon cream sauce today, it was to die for. It is also a very kid friendly restaurant!

title: Cafe Lago
text: Cafe Lago has been our go-to date night restaurant for years now. Always an excellent meal!

title: Cafe Lago
text: What can you say about a restaurant which has not lowered its standards in decades? Gnocchis which would float off your plate if they were not held down by a sublimely well balanced marinara. A lasagna as delicate as Thai silk...and I could go on and on. The service was discreet, smooth. A knowledgeable and friendly staff. The wine is well chosen and priced sensibly. Thank you Cafe Lago for still being part of the Seattle dining scene.

title: Cafe Lago
text: I would give Cafe Lago a five but no one believes anything is perfect. This place come pretty much close to that. A perfect neighborhood restaurant. Great atmosphere better food. Everything is FRESH, pasta and vegetables included. Not to mention the bartender makes a excellent cocktail if your into GREAT cocktails. I recommend any Seattleite to check this place out. People visiting Seattle should too!

title: Harry's Fine Foods
text: We've dined there two times for dinner now....I highly recommend trying whatever they have for a special that day. The Trout I had last week was simply incredible! Before that visit, they had a Salmon special that was equally as tasty and accompanied by interesting veggies and pickled delights. This is a neighborhood cafe, not a chain restaurant. Expect a casual culinary experience and again, go with what the chef has named a special of the day. My husband chefs at a local bed and breakfast, he's recommended Harry's to several guests who raved about it the following morning.

title: Bar Harbor
text: I lam ve the atmosphere of the place. The staff are so friendly. Food was good. I ordered a cold sandwich but i rather not order it again. It tasted good but i prefer a hot sandwich for lunch. The restaurant also close to donuts cafe. So we grabbed some donuts after lunch. I would recommend try this place at least once.

title: Americana Restaurant
text: This is a nice cute little restaurant. I‚Äôm still learning the Capitol Hill neighborhood and actually ended up here because Glo‚Äôs cafe was busy with a long wait time (which for me was totally understandable) so my friend I was with recommended this place and I‚Äôm happy she did. We were seated immediately wherever we liked, the sever was very kind and attentive! I had the French Toast and loved it!

title: Due' Cucina - Capitol Hill
text: Is this a super duper fancy restaurant where you wear your favorite dinner jacket and say rude things to the wait staff? No. In fact they yell out your name when your food is ready. Is the food here diverse, hand made with love, and crazy tasty? Oh heck yeah. They also have a spectrum of "really healthy" to "maybe it's healthy". It's an easy place to get awesome food, but it also has a classy and comfortable vibe like your favorite cafe; but with pasta. I think there was a guy at the counter with an Italian accent so that was a plus. Has pictures of famous people with quotes about food, but I don't remember seeing any cool art. If they don't have some art I think that would be a good addition.

title: Skillet Diner @ Capitol Hill
text: As an out of state visitor, it can be tough to find your way to a good local restaurant. Fortunately, this little cafe fulfilled all of our needs, so much so, that we went a second time before leaving town. The serving sizes alone are worth the money, but the food was all exceptional. On my first visit, the blackened chicken sandwich was more delicious than you'd expect a simple sandwich to be. On my second visit, the chicken and waffles was also more than meets the eye (it's made with cornmeal!) The drink menu is extensive and creative as well, plus the servers were attentive. Definitely make a point to stop by here if you're meandering through.

title: Lost Lake Cafe & Lounge
text: This is a real "locals" restaurant/bar. We were in Seattle over the Christmas holiday and hadn't booked any reservations for Christmas Eve dinner. So, my son did a little online research and found this Cafe had a special holiday menu that night, including a turkey, mashed potatoes & gravy, and cranberries! No reservations needed. We walked in and the "family" restaurant room was full, but we elected to sit in the bar. Great choice! The music was better, service was great and the food was really good (I did have the turkey special). It was a great mix of people too: race, gender, age, orientation...a fun melting pot of a real community. We had hot toddies with dinner and my daughter in law had a peppermint schnapps shake for dessert. It was s blast!

title: Lost Lake Cafe & Lounge
text: The perfect restaurant in town for picky eaters, families, college students, friend gatherings, and late-night freelancers (I've used the wifi here on my laptop and it works great! Power outlets are definitely much rarer though as it is much more of a restaurant than a cafe per se)

title: Lost Lake Cafe & Lounge
text: When you are visiting Seattle and suffering from jet lag or just finishing a night out- lost lake cafe offer's you a different option for food and drink during the wee hours. We had a good breakfast and found the food and service was fine. Definitely prefer this place to big chain 24hr restaurant's.

title: Lost Lake Cafe & Lounge
text:
Pretty bad all across the board. I've given it a few chances and have continually been stunned by the poor quality of food and zombie-like servers. I always give the benefit of the doubt as I'm a restaurant "lifer," but suckage is suckage. And it's available at Lost Lake Cafe.
JonJ

title: Cafe Con Leche
text: As a Cuban, it was a surprise to find a Cuban restaurant all the way out here in Seattle. The food was great, and let me say, the cafe con leche was supreme!

title: Cafe Con Leche
text:
Beware! This is not a Cuban owned nor operated restaurant although its said to be Cuban. I just recently visited this place hoping to eat some Cuban food since I'm not home and what a SAD surprise it was. To start, the staff is super rude. When I asked for a Cafe con Leche, they dont know how to make it. The dont know what a Cuban Toast and a Cortadito, yet they claim this is a Cuban restaurant.  When I asked if they were Cuban, they said very rudely "NO ARGENTINIANS" and in a very rude manner. And surely the food they cook isn't Cuban at all.

Best of luck if you decide to waste your money in this fraud of a restaurant.

title: Cafe Con Leche
text: Cafe Con Leche provides serviceable Cuban food. The Con Leche sandwich has good flavor. Passeo Caribbean is about a half mile north on 1st and provides bigger  messier sandwiches for about $2 more. Cafe Con Leche has a more sit down restaurant feel and better if you want quiet. Cafe Con Leche also has a big banquet hall with dance floor used for live bands and salsa lessons. Great place to drink with big groups or Latin music lovers alike...just be aware the food is second fiddle to the ambiance.

title: Cafe Con Leche
text: love this place the food taste like no other Cuban restaurant in the seattle area, if you are looking for an authentic Cuban restaurant cafe con leche is the place

title: Denny's
text: The Hangar Cafe had an hour wait, no place to sit at the Kauii Family Restaurant; but Denny's had us covered. And I gotta say my Build My Own omelette was excellent.

title: Easy Street Records & Cafe
text: Collection fun vibe. Food is solid for low prices. Cafe Vita Espresso bar in the restaurant. Large mimosas in a pint glass! Thick bacon. Great spot!

title: Easy Street Records & Cafe
text:
The record store is a one-of-a-kind and deserves 5 stars!
Cafe review only - The restaurant menu provides many different variations of egg, sausage, vegetable, and potato dishes. We anticipated the quality of the cafe food to be similar to a IHOP, and we found it met that level of American-style breakfast dishes. The welcoming staff were friendly and offered to come find us when a table was ready so that we could peruse the record store in search of artistic gems. The combination of the record store and cafe is an excellent idea, however, a little more attention to the quality of a few select dishes, rather than offering a long listed of similar dishes, would help to elevate the status of the cafe among local foodies. Being from out-of-state, we were pleasantly surprised to find the local farmers' market right outside of Easy Street Records & Cafe, making that an enjoy morning experience overall on a Sunday morning.

title: Easy Street Records & Cafe
text: Easy Street Cafe has the best bacon I've ever had at a restaurant. The wait can be a bit sometimes on the weekends after 9, however you can't beat their prices or... Did I mention their bacon! üòÇ

title: Taqueria La Jarochita
text: 16$ for average quality beef/rice burrito from a street food truck, not a restaurant or cafe is too expensive

title: Luna Park Cafe
text: Wow, so so glad we found Luna Park Cafe when we was visiting from England. This was exactly what we were looking for! A whole vegan menu, the food was absolutely delicious! Service was so good, really welcoming & friendly. The best food we ate whilst on our whole trip for sure‚Ä¶ We made sure we re visited before heading home and we really hope we will be back again in the future. If you‚Äôre looking for an awesome vegan breakfast, lunch or dinner with a cool setting inside the restaurant look no further! You‚Äôve got to try it out.  üòç

title: Luna Park Cafe
text: I accidently wrote a review of Luna Park cafe that was meant for an entirely different restaurant (the Blue Saucer Cafe - during the lunch hour, they were washing the windows by us using Windex while we were eating!! So gross!!) And it was a horrible restaurant, so I really screwed up. I can't honestly remember what I ordered at Luna the last time I was there, but it's a fun place, the people are great and the location is super easy when you consider it's in West Seattle! Totally worth going to!

title: East African Imports & Restaurant
text:
The observations and opinions of this experience,  is mine and mine alone.
Since Chef Caf√© is no longer in business and I have seen the owner of the aforementioned Cafe in this restaurant,  I tried it.
It's not bad,  it's not Baba's however is satisfies my craving for gomen and awaze lentils.
The ladies preparing and serving the food have uplifting smiles and positive attitudes.
I will definitely visit again.

title: Wonder Ethiopian Restaurant Sport Bar
text:
Update:
I‚Äôd say quality has gone down in the last two years they roll their injera and don‚Äôt put the platter for on the injera they place everything separate its like they‚Äôve changed for the white population, injera is not the same and shiro quality has went down their portions are small as well. I really like this place as they offer alcohol and live music but I can say it‚Äôs no longer worth the hype. You can see the reviewed pictures of how the platters are placed on different plates when that‚Äôs not how it‚Äôs supposed to be served at all

They‚Äôre priced a bit high for a new place, however their food is good, portions are a hit or miss. Sometimes they give you a decent portion other times they hide everything with injera and barely put any sauce in so I suggest checking before you leave. Their injera is good but their teff injera is okay. The restaurants atmosphere seems like they want to make it welcoming to Americans, which is good in Seattle. But their food also does not always seem authentic because of that, like they purposely make it less spicy. But they offer deli every and takeout later than any Ethiopian restaurant in Seattle so just by that they‚Äôre up points. Always friendly though and one of the few Ethiopian sports bars in Seattle that make it seem like they want everyone there (not my atmosphere I prefer Ethiopian/ Eritrean only) but hey in Seattle if you want your business to survive you adapt and I can respect that. I believe their chef is East African although I could not tell, she looked a bit Hispanic but she makes good food I was definitely a bit hesitant when I first went. They‚Äôre not my first choice but if Chefs Cafe or Kezira are closed then I will go here so definitely top 3 for Ethiopian restaurants although unlike Chefs and Kezira they do not offer Ayeb with your platter, not sure if it‚Äôs because it‚Äôs a veggie platter or what but their ayeb ‚Äúhouse cheese‚Äù is priced pretty high at $3 but they do give you a good amount. If you‚Äôre an American wanting to try a new place that feels welcoming however still cultural, this is your place but if you‚Äôre habesha I suggest ordering to go.

title: Nordstrom Grill
text:
A solid cafe style restaurant in the heart of of downtown Seattle! For what it is, I really appreciate the Nordstrom Grill. It's a very cozy dining experience with good food.

I got the Pomodoro pasta with shrimp and it was really good. I like the Pomodoro sauce and it had a little extra spice which I really appreciate even if it's not very traditional.

The location is also great. I love Nordstrom and this is located inside the Lish Nordstrom downtown. I would definitely come back for the sheer fact it's a great place to go after a nice shopping trip.

title: Taylor Shellfish Oyster Bar
text: Can't get any fresher.  Great place for seafood.  Not quite a restaurant setting, more of a cafe.  Good wine list as well

title: Bai Tong Thai Street Cafe
text: Wow!!! Can I just end there? Ok, no. I had an amazing dining experience at Bai Tong Thai Street Cafe restaurant! The wait staff were incredibly friendly and attentive throughout the meal, making me feel truly welcome. The food preparation was excellent, and every dish tasted authentic and delicious, transporting me back to Thailand with each bite. I ordered Northeastern Thai Sausage to start. Crispy Mussels Pancake as my main course. Finished off with Bua Lou Thai desert. I can't wait to return and savor those incredible flavors again!

title: Bai Tong Thai Street Cafe
text:
Gosh! What a thai cafe it is! I really thai food specially Panang & green curry, so happened to hit by this restaurant while taking a long walk in Capitol Hill.
This cafe is located right at the centre of Cap Hill, with no parking facility (but you can get Turbocharges & gas station with 500 yards).
I tried green chicken curry (oh man, those kafir lime leaves flavor üòç in it), Tofu fries & a glass of wheat beer stout.
Everything was amazing, do not expect to get free portion of rice, you need to pay extra $3 for it (but that‚Äôs ok üòä).
Tofu fries were sumptuous with cherry & peanut sauce.
Ambiance is great, staff is really helpful.
I would come to this place again!
